"Sunny California" is so named because much of it is arid and and has low atmospheric humidity.  Every year, a phenomenon known as the Santa Ana Winds sweep through southern California. Once houses go in to a wooded area, the homeowners do everything they can to suppress wildfires because who wants to live in a community with a bunch of charred tree trunks! Defensible Space Zones
Two zones make up the required 100 feet of defensible space.
Zone 1
Zone 1 extends 30 feet* from buildings, structures, decks, etc.

Remove all dead plants, grass and weeds (vegetation).
Remove dead or dry leaves and pine needles from your yard, roof and rain gutters.
Remove branches that hang over your roof and keep dead branches 10 feet away from your chimney.
Trim trees regularly to keep branches a minimum of 10 feet from other trees.
Relocate wood piles to Zone 2.
Remove or prune flammable plants and shrubs near windows.
Remove vegetation and items that could catch fire from around and under decks.
Create a separation between trees, shrubs and items that could catch fire, such as patio furniture, wood piles, swing sets, etc.
Zone 2
Zone 2 extends 100 feet out from buildings, structures, decks, etc.

Cut or mow annual grass down to a maximum height of 4 inches.
Create horizontal space between shrubs and trees. (See diagram)
Create vertical space between grass, shrubs and trees. (See diagram)

While the 2 million acres burned in California so far in 2020 is 10 times more area than burned in 2019, it‚Äôs still 2 million acres less than the lowest estimate for acres burned within modern state borders annually before Europeans settled in America. For most of the last 100 years, Californians suppressed fires in forests, resulting in the accumulation of roughly five times more wood fuel debris than existed in forests before Europeans arrived. 

Fires Aren‚Äôt New. High temperatures, forest fires, and smoky skies also occurred in California in the nineteenth century. While fire suppression has allowed the build-up of wood fuel in California‚Äôs mountain forests, such as the Sierra Nevadas, big, hot fires burned in southern California‚Äôs chaparral or shrubland forests in 1889, 1919, and 1932, long before fire suppression.


The US Forest Service adopted a policy of fire suppression. President Teddy Roosevelt and his Forest Service chief, Gifford Pinchot, drummed up fears of timber scarcity in order to expand federal control over forests and to suppress fires.

Public support for fire suppression, including from California‚Äôs elites, grew in the 1920s and 1930s after forest fires wiped out 1,000 homes in Berkeley, and burned 60,000 acres in Malibu. 

Within half a century, scientists realized that fire suppression was a mistake. Vast amount of fuels had accumulated for 50 or more years. The fires became far bigger than what could easily be handled. So, It's not entirely climate change but a cycle of nature.
